7 takeaways from the #G7Summit vis-a-vis China⬇️

1. UK's Rishi Sunak said China poses "the greatest challenge of our age" amid Beijing's increasing authoritarianism at home and broad. The CCP's Confucius Institute network across Western universities acts as a PR shield to soften Beijing's image abroad. These financially-linked contracts frequently carry strict conditions of censorship around topics like Tibet, Xianjing, and Taiwanese independence.

2. "De-risking" from China. The Asian giant is the global nerve center for global supply chains, and therefore holds significant leverage. Diversifying supply chains is another way to erode China's ability to use economic coercion on developed and emerging market economies. 

3. Reinforcing multilateral efforts among Western-aligned countries to control exports of strategic technologies. These include semiconductor chips in particular, as well as a crackdown on Beijing's industrial-scale, stake-backed efforts to steal hegemon-defining tech. 

4. Chinese and Russian officials at the summit hit back, claiming the West is forming an anti-China, anti-Russian coalition. Moscow and Beijing have also grown closer and are expanding a regional bulwark against Europe and the US. In addition to BRICS, the SCO, BRI, and other multilateral initiatives, Beijing recently hosted a summit with the five Central Asian states (Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan). The efforts are part of Xi Jinping's strategy to economically and financially integrate strategic, regional states in his anti-Western coalition.  

5. US-Australia alliance on joint efforts to tackle climate change and "enhancing cooperation on critical minerals". China's near-monopoly on processing rare earth metals and investments in Africa (particularly Congo where ~70% of the world's cobalt lies) gives it a strategic advantage. 

6. Fresh sanctions (11th package) were announced against Russia  that "focuses on circumventions" of corporate entities. No doubt, these efforts will only further de-tangle Russia from the West and simultaneously strengthen their ties with China and the East.
